<subSubSection id="2CDE41C4F52A3F4B4B10ECDBFB77C97B" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph id="647B124FF52A3F4B4B10ECDBFDABC4C6" blockId="38.[301,1701,791,2067]" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">
Fifty-six eggs were laid in a glass vial on June 8. When freshly laid, the eggs are white and are covered with a somewhat longitudinally striated, transparent layer of mucus which is drawn out at the micropylar end. The egg is 
<quantity id="A33CBFAAF52A3F4B4B4EEB24FE35C51F" box="[302,465,1100,1143]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="0.75">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4B4EEB24FE92C51F" box="[302,374,1100,1143]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">0.75</emphasis>
mm
</quantity>
. long and 
<quantity id="A33CBFAAF52A3F4B48FBEB24FCC3C51F" box="[667,807,1100,1143]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
. at its greatest width. It is oblong-oval, broadly rounded on one side and scarcely rounded on the other, rounded posteriorly, and with micropylar end carinate around a relatively small cap, the diameter across cap half that of greatest diameter of egg. The chorion is very smooth, polished, without spines and processes, and the egg thus resembles eggs of 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF52A3F4B4B4DEA25FE31C41F" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[301,469,1357,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Reduvius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4B4DEA25FE31C41F" box="[301,469,1357,1399]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">Reduvius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF52A3F4B4857EA25FD38C41F" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1832" box="[567,732,1357,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Triatoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4857EA25FD38C41F" box="[567,732,1357,1399]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">Triatoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than those of 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF52A3F4B4E05EA25FAF6C41F" authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[1125,1298,1357,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Emesinae">Emesinae</taxonomicName>
. Incubation period of eggs, eight days.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="647B124FF52A3F4B4B0CEADEFB77C97B" blockId="38.[301,1701,791,2067]" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF52A3F4B4B0CEADEFD91C488" authorityName="Usinger" authorityYear="1946" box="[364,629,1462,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Polytoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marianensis">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4B0CEADEFD91C488" box="[364,629,1462,1504]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">P. marianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very close to the Philippine 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4EC0EADEFA60C488" box="[1184,1412,1462,1504]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">fuscovittatus</emphasis>
Stal in size and coloration but the pronotal spines in that species, according to Distant (Fauna Brit. 
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF52A3F4B4BF3E973FE15C72F" box="[403,497,1563,1607]" name="India" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">India</collectingCountry>
, Rhynch. 2: 219, 1904), are &quot;about as long as pronotum.'' A more detailed comparison is impossible because of the inadequate descriptions of the Philippine species. 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF52A3F4B48E9E9EBFCD4C7C5" authorityName="China" authorityYear="1930" box="[649,816,1667,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Polytoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B48E9E9EBFCD4C7C5" box="[649,816,1667,1709]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">P. similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF52A3F4B495FE9EBFC41C7C5" box="[831,933,1667,1709]" name="China" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">China</collectingCountry>
from 
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF52A3F4B4E7AE9EBFB6BC7C5" box="[1050,1167,1667,1709]" name="Samoa" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">Samoa</collectingCountry>
is much larger with relatively longer second antenna! segment, more acute and upright metanotal spine, and convex sides of female genital plate. A male from Houailou, 
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF52A3F4B4FEAE982F97AC67C" box="[1418,1694,1770,1812]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, agrees with 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF52A3F4B4863E875FD31C620" authorityName="Usinger" authorityYear="1946" box="[515,725,1821,1864]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Polytoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marianensis">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4863E875FD31C620" box="[515,725,1821,1864]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">marianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in size and in genital characters but the pronotal spines are much smaller, only one seventh as long as width of pronotum across humeri, and the color is quite different, the head, pronotum, and legs being tinged with red. The male genitalia resemble those of 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF52A3F4B4E40E8DCFAEFC689" box="[1056,1291,1972,2017]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="49">selangorensis</emphasis>
Miller but that species is smaller with relatively longer pronotal spines.
</paragraph>
